INT. FARMHOUSE KITCHEN - DAWN

Grey light leaks through a cracked window. MARGARET ELLERBY, 60s, weathered and certain, sets a kettle on the stove.

A floorboard creaks behind her.

MARGARET
You're up early.

THOMAS (O.S.)
Couldn't sleep.

THOMAS ELLERBY, 30s, stands in the doorway, coat already on.

THOMAS
The bank wrote again.

MARGARET
(not turning)
I read it.

THOMAS
And?

MARGARET
And we plant the long field today. Same as we planned.

She pours two cups. The steam rises between them.

EXT. THE LONG FIELD - DAY

Endless furrows under a hard sky. Thomas drives the old tractor. Margaret walks the seed line behind him.

MARGARET (V.O.)
My grandfather broke this ground. My father held it. I am not the one who loses it.

The tractor coughs, sputters — and dies.

THOMAS
No. No, no, no.

He jumps down, throws open the engine housing. Smoke.

MARGARET
Thomas.

THOMAS
I can fix it.

MARGARET
Thomas. Look.

She points to the ridge. A line of NEIGHBOURS — a dozen of them — crest the hill, tools on their shoulders, walking down toward the field.

THOMAS (CONT'D)
(quietly)
You called them.

MARGARET
I didn't have to.

CUT TO:

EXT. THE LONG FIELD - DUSK

The field is sown. The neighbours gather at the fence, dusty and spent. Margaret stands among them, smaller now, and somehow taller.

MARGARET
Thank you. All of you.

> THE END <

= Margaret refuses to sell; the community plants the field together.

# Act One

= Setup: the debt, the deadline, the decision to plant anyway.
